</LOCATION>, in 1969. He recently sold the $ 160 million-a-year engineering company to devote his time to the Black Hills effort. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 58, supports legislation introduced by Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, that would return 1.3 million acres of federal land in the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> region was deeded to the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Laramie </LOCATION> Treaty of 1868. But after gold was discovered by an expedition led by Lt. Col. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> <PERSON> Custer </PERSON>, prospectors swarmed in and the treaty was abrogated in 1877. The Indians were forced onto reservations in less desirable parts of the state. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 upheld a settlement for the land, which with interest has grown to nearly $ 200 million. Most of the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> tribal governments have refused the money, saying they want the land. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s bill would return about 1.3 million of the land covered by the original treaty. It applies only to federal land in the area of timbering, mining and tourism, and does not include <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rushmore </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> argues the <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> also should get up to $ 3.1 billion for their loss of revenue since the land was taken. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s bill, introduced two years ago and still not out of committee, is opposed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>'s congressional delegation. Many backers of <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s bill say <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' plan to seek additional money would wreck the bill's chances in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.
